    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i've also been reading about the criticisms of it. people seem to say originalism is just a way for judges to push a specific political agenda under the guise of law. how do scholars usually respond to that claim that it's more about politics than actual interpretation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics who claim originalism is merely a political disguise fundamentally misunderstand its core premise. Originalists argue that fidelity to the text is the *only* legitimate constraint on judicial power, not a political tool. If a judge interprets the Constitution based on their personal feelings, they are engaging in judicial activism, which is inherently political. Therefore, adhering to the original public meaning is the most objective and least political form of legal reasoning available.",
